text: Haycock is an unincorporated community and mining camp in the Nome Census Area, Alaska, United States. ==History== The community was founded in 1914 as a mining camp; it had a post office from 1916 until 1957. ==Demographics== Haycock first appeared on the 1920 U.S. Census as an unincorporated village. It appeared again in 1930 and 1940. It has not returned since. ==Notable person== *William E. Beltz, carpenter and politician, was born in Haycock.'Last Rites For Beltz Held Today,' Faorbanks Daily News Miner, November 23, 1960, pg. 1 ==Notes== Category:Unincorporated communities in Nome Census Area, Alaska Category:Unincorporated communities in Alaska Category:Mining communities in Alaska
title: Haycock, Alaska
